		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message29381343">In defense of Hajime and, ahem, Paiman (the so-called panda thing): they're supposed to act like that. I think it's unfair to judge their characters based on our perception of how humans should behave, and there're lots of times when I've found cultural impediments to be detrimental in understanding what a work may be trying to convey.<br />
<br />
That said, it's reasonable to critique a character's actions and their stakes or logic in doing something. In this case, Hajime and Paiman (who are two of the few okay/good characters in this show) act in accordance to the comedic and relaxing mood of the story. And there's nothing wrong with their casual dispositions. However, if one were to say that they act inappropriately in dramatic scenes or such, I'd agree to some extents. Their silliness do feel dissonant with the presented drama at times.<br />
<br />
The villain(s) in this show are deplorable. Everything about them: either are cliched or their actions simply intolerable, illogical on many levels. Some of the Gatchamen's back-stories and characterizations could use some work.The ending about democracy or whatever was nonsensical; it made me cringe at how much substance the director threw out the window in lieu of some flash and bombast. Not only was it confusing, it ruined a lot of the build-up. <br />
<br />
So in summary, I like Hajime, the fun stuff at the beginning, the music, and the animation. But that's about it. If the second season doesn't have another crappy villain plot it'd be 10x better.</div><div class="postActions"></div></td>
		</tr></table></div><div class="forum_boardrowspacer">&nbsp;</div>
